ont-size:11pt">Wherever possible schools work together</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and are given positive incentives to do so,</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to improve student outcomes and create a sustainable and self-improving system</span></li><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sponsors and chains are transparently held to account a</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gainst a clear framework and should use their unique positions to benefit </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> schools as well as </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their own</span></li><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A middle-tier</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that includes a range</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of stakeholders</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is introduced to </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academies and free schools</span></li><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Appropriate incentives for</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and alternatives to</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academisation are offered to primary schools </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SSAT’s </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">educational o</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">utlook</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As will become apparent through the direct responses to the Committee’s questions, at the heart of SSAT’s mission is a belief in a self-improving school system,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in which school leaders become system leaders with a shared vision for educational outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that this will be achieved through meaningful collaboration between schools, policy makers, educational theorists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, employers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and other stakeholders. SSAT believes in the importance of networks, both formal and informal, to do this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SSAT has articulated this aim through our Redesigning Schooling campaign, which supports schools in sharing and disseminating best and innovate pra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ctices; thus realising a vision for system-wide transformation. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">With reference to </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the Committee’s</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> specific questions</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the acad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">emies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is certainly some evidence to suggest sponsored academies, that have taken control of failing schools, are making progress in closing the attainment gap as they improve the sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ools more generally.  The picture is less clear, however, when it comes to converter academies, who although performing well, are not necessarily </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">closing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the gap for disadvantaged children.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> point raised by Sir Michael Wilshaw in Ofsted’s recent annual r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eport. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is SSAT’s belief that this demonstrates that academisation is not a panacea that on its own will raise schools’ achievement and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">close</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the educational gap.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cademies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> use their freedoms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">engage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in collaboration with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">real peer challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and be given access to appropriate support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to do so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It must also be acknowledged that there are alternatives to academisation which can also bring about a positive impact on student outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In a report authored jointly by The Schools Network and Refo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rm in 2012, which sampled data from a wide range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SSAT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academy members, it was demonstrated that just 31 per cent of sampled academies had made changes to the curriculum following academisation.  Often, these changes would have been possible prior to aca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">demisation anyway. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Those schools that do use the freedoms they have gained are often those that perform most highly and are most successful in closing the gap.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It is therefore imperative that academies are encouraged, where appropriate, to use their fre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">edoms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and do not feel constrained</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by accountability measures.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, just using their autonomy is not enough.  All schools, academies or otherwise, benefit from collaborating with other schools when this provides real peer support and challenge.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">body of evidence for the benefits of collaboration and school partnerships is large and corroborated by the experience of SSAT members.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Indeed, the Committee recognised in its recent inquiry: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Schools partnership and Cooperation,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that collaboration betwee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n schools has huge potential to drive up standards. Academies are no different and to truly transform student outcomes they should be working in networks and collaborating as a matter of course.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is also worth noting that there is a varied interpretat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion of how Pupil Premium money should be used in schools.  Whether it should solely be pointed to students on free school meals or to students who underperform, as these two things are not the same.  Clarification </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on this matter and exactly how the money c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an be used would be welcomed and could give schools an opportunity to further improve student outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">including working with sponsors</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SSAT believe that academisation is not a panacea and that at any given time academy status is not always appropriate for schools.  As such, compelling schools to become academies is not a measure SSAT supports.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A pragmatic approach that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">takes into conside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the complexities of the contexts of schools must be applied and other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">options</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> explored</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> before schools are compelled to become academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is clear that any sponsors wishing to establish academies or free schools need to undergo a rigorous evalua</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion against a transparent set of criteria prior to approval.  Where possible this should include evidence of prior impact and success.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly, after establishing schools, sponsors need to be monitored carefully and demonstrate impact before they are a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">llowed to expand.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a marked difference between a successful school opening a free school and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> group with no prior experience of running schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> doing so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It must be clear that sponsors have the knowledge and expertise to manage a sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ool successfully.  And just because a school is successful in one context does not mean it will necessarily be successful in setting up and running another school.  The capacity of school sponsors must be taken into consideration before allowing them to es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tablish schools to avoid the sponsor schools letting their own standards slip.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, academies and free schools should be given access to appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">initial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support.  In the past </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> benefited from a bespoke school improvement resource (the ASP); this made a significant impact on standards in their first year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  As well as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">direct support, free schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could benefit from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> more general</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support prior to opening.  SSAT’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">membership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> network is a good example of how such support can be offered.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The availability of support such as this, especially in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the early years of an academy or free school’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> life, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can ensure their success.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There also needs to be a focus on where academ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies and free schools are established in order to address capacity shortage.  New schools should be placed in areas of need and any impact of a new school on the local landscape needs to be carefully considered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regardless of the competence of the sponsors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> before it is given the go-ahead.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Secretary of State’s role should be a solely strategic one.  Intervention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for failing schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should come from an appropri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate middle-tier who have local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">knowledge and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> practical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">held to account by the Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Schools should be very much involved in this and i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f succes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it would constitute part of a self-sustaining and self-improving system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such a middle-tier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would need to incorporate local knowledge and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">involve input from schools themselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">range</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Its role should be to coordinate supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ort and challenge,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> broker links and partnerships between schools and to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> intervene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, or coordinate intervention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if absolutely necessary.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  The ability to broker nuanced links through a fundamental understanding of the schools it works with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">both</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">networks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would be crucial to the success of a middle-tier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in raising standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The success of SSAT schemes such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Raising Achievement, Transforming Learning (RATL) and Gaining Ground</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where SSAT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">carefully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brokered links between schools to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">drive school improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> demonstrate the importance of this.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The London Challenge is a good example of how such a system can work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on a large and regional scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, incorporating schools,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> stakeholders,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> experts and a coordinating body with strategic oversight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to allow all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">involved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to work together </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">successfully</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It is important that schools view any middle-tier as a mechanism for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improvement, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support and challenge and have some involvement with it.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rtantly, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ny middle-tier must not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be able to dictate to schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or inhibit any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of their freedoms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If it were to simply add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> layer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of bureaucracy and accountability to the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> then it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would not be effective.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It is SSAT’s belief that a middle-tier a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s outlined above would have the potential to coordinate and lead sustained improvement.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is noted that plans have recently come to light for ‘Headteacher Boards’ to monitor academies and free schools in eight separate units of the country.  Whilst we co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mmend the notion of outstanding heads with local knowledge being utilised to aid failing schools we are wary that academy freedoms should not be inhi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bited by the proposed scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">headteachers are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not overburdened</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and that no conflicts of interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are created.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We wait with interest to see more detailed plans.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore school-to-school support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can be very</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> beneficial to failing schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">when conducted appropriately.  T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Secretary of State can aid this by creating conditions conducive to collabor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation and incentivising schools to support others.  However, there is a clear difference between creating appropriate conditions for collaboration and setting it out as a mandate.  Forcing schools to collaborate and aid failing schools is unlikely to prove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as effective as stimulating it organically.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">nd responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The experience of SSAT’s members in relation to local authorities varies immensely and this situation is not aided by the current lack of clarity on their role.  W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hilst local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ statutory obligations are relatively clear their role in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> relation to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> school improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is far less </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As such their powers and responsibilities, specifically in relation to school improvement, need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clarified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clear though that local authorities should be more involved in the strategic planning for new schools to ensure they are located where there is a need for more school places or greater choice.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is also important to note that of our members who are acade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mies approximately half still procure their backroom services from the local authority.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Furthermore, many primary schools still rely heavily on local authority support.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  This is demonstrative of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> types of service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> they can still offer to schools.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r experience gaps in support for schools are often down to geographical location.  Urban schools benefit from being relatively close to a large number of schools allowing them to develop beneficial links.  More rural schools are less likely to benefit from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such support and would be helped by a more structured middle-tier, in line with that outlined above, where local authority and school support is lacking.  It is important to note here that there are some exceptional examples of regional practice.  SSAT, f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">works with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a group of deputy heads in West Sussex who meet regularly to provide support and challenge for each other. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As already suggested there is a need for a middle-tier to exist between the Secretary of State and individual schools.  Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ideas are outlined in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> response to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> previous question.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Academy chains are in a go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">od position to monitor and support the schools that they govern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he best chains</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have the relevant knowledge and experience to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do just that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, all chains </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> held appropriately to account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for their actions and governance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This needs to be done against a coherent and transparent accountability framework.  Whilst their position lends itself to a role in monitoring and intervening, and we believe they should be given support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to do so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, any role that academy chains can fulfil sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould not be to the exclusion of an accountable middle-tier.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What is also clear is that academy chains are well placed to disseminate good practice and instigate formal collaboration between its schools.  We would encourage this as much as possible.  Howev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er, it is also important that chains do not become overly inward focussed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and collaborate with, support and challenge schools outside of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> formal network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as within it.  This should include accessing best practice nationally and internationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply; and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">majority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of SSAT members have indicated that they think academy conversion for individual primary schools will hold little to no benefit for them.  Due to the relative size and resource of individual primary schools the task of actually administering conversion an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d then taking on the extra work that that can entail going forward means academisation is unappealing.  Primary schools often simply have fewer staff than secondary schools that can commit time to conversion.  As a result there are relatively few opportuni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ties to benefit from economies of scale and indeed some members have suggested the challenges presented by individual primary conversion may well outweigh the benefits.  This would suggest that for individual schools academisation does not represent value </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for money.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, these members do feel that conversion as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> part of a chain, group or umbrella arrangement is more likely to be successful as it would create the capacity for support and challenge as well as increasing the potential economies of scale. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urthermore if there was any potential to outsource work (whilst maintaining independence, rigour and control) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the sources of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> extra funding available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to schools with low pupil-rolls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were better publicised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and  understood </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">then this could also incentiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ise primary schools becoming academies.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Value for money is, of course, an important consideration but this does not necessarily have to come about through academy status.  Primary schools can and have formed clusters or partnerships to cut costs by poolin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g resources centrally without the need to be an academy.  Importantly though, whether academy or not, schools working together should not see it solely as a cost cutting initiative but take the opportunity to develop pedagogy and share best practice.  If p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rimaries are keen to come together in groups to benefit from academisation it is likely that advice and guidance will be needed in order for them to take full advantage and ensure it has a positive impact in all schools and not only on finances.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What alt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ernatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The definition of failing needs to be clear and the capacity of a school to improve must be taken into account before radical intervention is made.  That being said, SSAT su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pport a rigorous system and believe that where a school is genuinely failing it should not be allowed to continue without intervention.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> However, considering that the process of becoming an academy can provide a significant burden for a small primary school and that at any given time academy status is not always appropriate it is imperative that other options are presented to primary schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is our belief that these should primarily focus on facilitating school-to-school support.  This could include federations or clusters with local outstanding primaries who have the resource to aid the failing school as well as softer forms of collab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oration with local schools and strategic partners.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It will also be important to develop and nurture the next generation of primary leaders so that there is the human capital in place to prevent primaries from failing and to turn those around that unfortun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ately do.  There is need for a supported framework of leadership training and opportunities for primary staff to develop their leadership capacity.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Other Notes</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given that the questions focus on system changes and improved performance, it is concerning that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">special schools have not been included in the remit of this Committee i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nquiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The issues of improving the quality of teaching and learning, effective leadership, rigorous governance and improved pupil outcomes is just as relevant for those with high leve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l special educational needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as others.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expectations and principles of effective practice should be consistent across all our state funded educational institutions.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wherever possible schools work together to improve student outcomes and </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">create a sustainable and self-improving system</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sponsors and chains are transparently held to account against a clear framework and should use their unique positions to benefit other schools as well as their own</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A middle-tier, that includes a range of </span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stakeholders, is introduced to support academies and free schools</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Appropriate incentives for, and alternatives to, academisation are offered to primary schools </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We hope that this is of value to your consultation.  SSAT would be more than happy to contrib</span><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ute further and look forward to reading your final report.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#282828; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">SSAT &amp; Reform, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Plan A+: Unleashing the Potential of Academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, (2012).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> J. Campbell, </